    "### OPEN AI SDK Example"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "61b88282",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Here are some fun facts about data engineering — short and a little surprising:\n",
      "\n",
      "1. Data engineering predates “big data.”  \n",
      "   The ETL and data-warehouse ideas go back to the 1970s–1990s, long before Hadoop or Spark made “big data” a buzzword.\n",
      "\n",
      "2. Data engineers are the plumbers of tech.  \n",
      "   They build and maintain the pipes that move data — unseen but essential, and often blamed when things leak.\n",
      "\n",
      "3. SQL is older than the web.  \n",
      "   SQL was developed in the early 1970s at IBM — years before the internet became mainstream — yet it’s still one of the most-used tools in data work.\n",
      "\n",
      "4. Most of the job is cleaning and wrangling.  \n",
      "   Analysts and engineers often say the majority of time on projects goes to fixing and preparing data, not the fancy analytics or models.\n",
      "\n",
      "5. Pipelines can become “legacy monuments.”  \n",
      "   Some ETL jobs and batch pipelines have been running (and evolving) in production for decades — and outlive many applications they feed.\n",
      "\n",
      "6. Small fixes can have huge impact.  \n",
      "   A tiny change in a pipeline (a wrong timezone, an off-by-one, a missing null-handling) can cascade into big business decisions — good reason data engineers add many tests and monitoring.\n",
      "\n",
      "Want one fun anecdote or a short story about a specific data-engineering mishap or win?\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import os\n",
    "from dotenv import load_dotenv\n",
    "from openai import OpenAI\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "client = OpenAI()\n",
    "\n",
    "response = client.responses.create(\n",
    "    model=\"gpt-5-mini\",\n",
    "    input=\"Tell me fun fact about data engineering\"\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(response.output_text)\n"
   ]
